,Recommended,298480,14641388,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,Lord Reefer,"This game was everything I was hoping for and more. The UI is both very simple and powerful. The game gives you a grand array of choice, both in ships, factions and campaigns. The campaigns are fully dynamic, in the spirit of Mount and Blade, and fully replayable. It has random events and elements you would expect from a roguelike. There is no annoying narrative or forced choices, you're more of a pirate than a naval officer. The game runs smoothly, takes up little space and does not crash. From what I have seen, the developer heavily supports this game post launch. It is over all a very well put together experience.This being said, there are many things this game could improve on. First of all, the audio design is the worst I've heard in a while. This is very detrimental to the atmosphere in this game. The ships make silly noises, a la Willhelm Scream, when they sink. All the guns have the same 3 or 4 loops. The impacts of all weapons sound the same. This being said, the 2d and the FX are only slightly better. Namely, the charachter faces and shell FX.For some reason, I can't edit the names of my Captains or ships. Something I got used to in these types of games. There is also no ship customization. However, the sheer number of different ships partially fills this role.The Campaign could use a bit more bells and whistles. Such as larger number of mission types, enemy formations, etc.Kudos to the Devs, hope to see a Soviet Navy soon!"
