,Not Recommended,298480,17378687,"Posted: 3 August, 2015",all,Longshot2025,"Got this on sale and really wanted to like it. Wasn't looking for a realistic simulator or even a big challenge, so that didn't bother me. As of 1.3 you can play as both the allied and axis in the Pacific, Atlantic and Mediterranean.Basic premise for the campaigns is the same: start with one port and one destroyer and go from there. You get missions that seem to be randomly generated. Examples include: attack groups of ships in a certain area, deliver a document from one port to another (read: visit one port and then go straight to the next), destroy a given convoy, attack a port. You get the idea. Nothing particularly unique to see here.You get war bonds by completing misssions and destorying enemy ships. You can then buy more ships. Let's talk about ships. By default, you can buy ships from any allied nation (e.g. a US player can buy UK and French ships). I'd recommend turning this off so you don't have dozens of nearly identical ships to choose from. Even within this constraint you'll find yourself comparing ships with tiny differences between one another. I still have no idea if having more crew is supposed to be good or bad. Campaing gameplay is basically grinding out experience and war bonds to unlock and purchase bigger and better ships, and then amassing a fleet that can overpower anything else.Gameplay is alright. Calling the AI useless is the nicest thing you can say about it.The UI is lacking in many ways. It would be nice if the game followed RTS conventions when it came to left and right-click for select and move/attack.The game tosses up tutorial videos before each fight, which is okay but not the best method to get you the most important and relevant info. For instance, I got the lesson about formations when I only had two ships, so there was no need to actually consider using formations until later in the game.Graphics are worthy of a mobile game. Ships are arguably the worst, which is odd considering they should be the main focus. Water and smoke are pretty good. Explosions are unimpressive. Sound is generic. All explosions/crew dying/shots firing sound pretty much the same. As far as I can tell the soundtrack consists of precisely one track.The day/night cycle's only affect on gameplay is that you cannot see other fleets from as far away at night, and you cannot tell their composition from any distance. In the actual battles, there's no difference that I can see.In battles, nearby fleets will attempt to reinforce both sides, usually with a 5-7 minute ETA. Unfortunately there's frequently no way to tell before entering the fight what reinforcements (if any) will partake and how long it will be until they arrive. This makes it hard to plan on if you have enough ships to win the fight, or if reinforcements will cause problems. Additionally, port attacks require AI controlled landing craft to make it safely to shore. Given how slow these are you'd expect reinforcement times to play an important role, but as long as you destroy the initial defenders, you automatically take the port, and the supposedly one minute away reinforcements don't matter at all.There's a good game idea buried in here somewhere, but for $25 USD you can get much better games."
